# **INTRODUCTION**

![][image1]

***OmniHammer is a tabletop miniature game set in the far, grim, dark future where humans and alien races fight for survival and dominion across a corrupt, malevolent galaxy.***  

To play a game of OmniHammer, each player chooses a faction to play and assembles an **ARMY** of miniature models, organized into fighting **UNITS** as described in the **CODEX** book for their faction. The **POINT VALUE** of each players’ army cannot exceed the agreed upon **POINT LIMIT** determined by both players before the game begins.

To begin a game, players will arrange terrain features on a tabletop surface representing the **BATTLEFIELD**. Players will choose a **MISSION** for the battle, which determines the specific scoring **OBJECTIVES** for the current battle and other special rules that govern the mission. Finally, players will **DEPLOY** their forces to the table and get ready to take the first turn.

Once the battle starts, players alternate taking a **PLAYER TURN** once each **BATTLE ROUND**, activating and using their forces during their turn. Players will maneuver their units around the board, conduct ranged attacks, and orchestrate brutal close combat engagements. When the mission’s end condition is triggered \- usually after a certain number of battle rounds \- the victorious player is determined based on how well they accomplished the mission’s scoring objectives, and of course how well they took the fight to their opponent\!

# **CORE ELEMENTS**

![][image2]

This section describes the fundamental playing pieces and organizational terms used in the game.

## **ARMIES**

Each player commands an **ARMY** of fighting **UNITS**, comprised of one or more **MODELS**, as described in their faction’s **CODEX** book. These units are organized into a **DETACHMENT** that governs how many units of a certain type may be combined into a player’s army. Before the game, players must decide on a **POINT LIMIT** for the battle, and the total point value of each player’s army may not exceed the decided point limit (see [ASSEMBLING AN ARMY](#assembling-an-army)).

## **MODELS** {#models}

Models are all of the physical playing pieces that make up a player’s army.  Models are of two broad types: **FIGURINE** models and **VEHICLE** models.  Rules that refer to a “model” are assumed to apply to both types unless a specific type is referenced.

#### **FIGURINE MODELS (aka NON-VEHICLE MODELS)**

* **TYPES OF FIGURINE MODEL:** Each figurine model is assigned a type (see [UNIT TYPES](#unit-types-summary)).  A model’s type determines details about its movement, shooting attacks, melee attacks, and other abilities. Figurine model types include: 

  **INFANTRY, BIKES, JETBIKES, CAVALRY, BEASTS,** 

  **MONSTROUS CREATURES, FLYING MONSTERS, ARTILLERY, CHARACTERS**

* **BODY**: The “body” of a figurine model includes its head, upper/lower torso, backpacks, legs, and arms.  Hands, feet, claws, banner poles, weapons, fins, or other smaller appendages do not count as part of the model’s body.  
* **BASES:** Figurine models have a **BASE** of a certain size, which is supplied with the model.  
* **MODEL HEIGHT:** For figurine models, its height is measured from the table surface to the top of the body (which includes the head), including the thickness of the base. 


#### **VEHICLE MODELS**

* **TYPES OF MODEL:** Each vehicle model is assigned one or more types, which determine details about it’s movement, shooting attacks, melee attacks, and other special rules. Vehicle types include: 

  **TANK, FAST, SKIMMER, FLYER, OPEN-TOPPED, WALKER, CHARIOT, TRANSPORT**

* **HULL:** For vehicle models, the **HULL** is any part of the main exterior shell or structure of the vehicle, including any turrets or larger sub-structures.  Antenna, exhaust pipes, fins, banners, gun barrels, or other appendages to the vehicle that stick out from the main body do not count as part of the hull.  
  * **BASES:** Vehicle models with bases, such as walkers, flyers, and skimmers, ignore their base for all purposes.  Distances are always measured to the vehicle’s hull.  
* **VEHICLE HEIGHT:** For vehicle models, the height is measured from the table surface to the tallest part of the hull and/or turrets (whichever is tallest).   
* **VEHICLE FACING:** Vehicles have different **FACINGS** that affect which side of a vehicle takes damage when attacked.  Facings are 90-degree arcs, with a front facing, two side facings, and a rear facings. These arcs originate at the **Center Point** of the model, which is located at the intersection of the midway line and the central axis of the hull (see diagram below).




**MODEL BASES**

* Models which cannot stand freely by themselves must be attached to a base.  
* The model must be able to fit wholly on the base (a toe poking over an edge is acceptable).  
* Specific base sizes for models are not enforced, provided that the model looks reasonable (no Tyranid Hormagaunts on 80mm bases for example) on the base and can stand without tipping under reasonable and normal play conditions such as the table being bumped while reaching across it or the model being placed on a slight incline on terrain.

**WHAT YOU SEE IS WHAT YOU GET (WYSIWYG**)

* OmniHammer is intended to be played with fully painted models that have all their wargear represented correctly on their model.  
* If one player has an army that is both fully painted and follows WYSIWYG and the other player does not, the player with the painted WYSIWYG army may choose to go first or second without needing to roll off.

**PROXIES/3D PRINTED MODELS**

* Proxies, scratch-builds, and 3D printed models are always encouraged, provided it is obvious what model they are representing and they are of inoffensive quality. Models which are otherwise offensive are acceptable.

## **UNITS**

A **UNIT** is the primary element used in the game to organize and manage your fighting forces.

* **UNIT:** One or more models taken from the same **DATASHEET** entry in a codex.   
* **DATASHEET:** The datasheet describes the minimum and maximum number of models allowed in the unit, the type of standard or optional equipment models may take, special rules, and the model’s **CHARACTERISTIC PROFILE**.  
* **SQUADRONS:** Units composed of multiple vehicles are called **SQUADRONS**.

### Starting Strength & Half Strength

* **STARTING STRENGTH:** A unit’s starting strength is the number of models in the unit at the start of the game.  
* **CURRENT STRENGTH**: A unit’s current strength is the number of models in the unit at the START of the current player’s turn.  
* **HALF STRENGTH:** A unit is at half strength when it contains LESS than 50% of it’s starting strength.  
* **ALL ON THEIR OWN:** If a unit that originally consisted of at least five models is reduced to a single model, that model may move, shoot, and assault on its own as if it were a unit. The model is treated as a unit of one for all rules purposes and is not considered to be at half strength for the purposes of pinning modifiers.

### Coherency & Engagement

#### **COHERENCY**

* Models in a unit must strive to maintain **COHERENCY** during the course of play.  
* **COHERENCY:** Models in a unit are in coherency if all models are in one continuous chain and within within 2” horizontally for non-vehicle units (or 6” for **Vehicle Squadrons**) AND within 5” vertically of at least one another model in the unit, as measured between the bases of a model (or hulls for vehicle models)  
* **MAXIMUM COHERENCY:** No two models in a unit may be further apart than 18”.


#### **ENGAGED MODELS**

* A model counts as **ENGAGED** if it is in base-to-base contact with an opposing model (except for non-walker vehicles) or it is within 1” of a friendly model that is in base-to-base contact with an opposing model.    
* **ENGAGED UNITS:** If any models in a unit are engaged, the unit as a whole is also treated as being **engaged and locked in a melee engagement**.  
* Note: If a model has sufficient movement to be placed in base-to-base contact with an enemy model, but the bases cannot physically touch due to pose of the model or incidental terrain features making it hard to place models, they are still treated as if in base-to-base contact.

## **CHARACTERISTICS**

Every model has a characteristic profile that describes the attributes and properties of the model.  These characteristics are used in many ways throughout the game.

### Standard Model Profile

Figurine models use a **PROFILE** like shown in the example below, which displays the model’s **CHARACTERISTIC** values.

		**WS	BS	S	T	W	I	A	Ld	Sv**  
**Imperial Guard**	  3	 3	3	3	 1	3	1	6	5+

#### **CHARACTERISTICS**

* **(WS) Weapon skill**: The model’s ability to hit enemy units with melee attacks.  
* **(BS) Ballistic Skill**: The model’s ability to hit targets with ranged shooting attacks.  
* **(S) Strength:** A measure of how powerful a unit’s melee attacks are.  
* **(T) Toughness:** A measure of how well the model can avoid wounds through their durability.  
* **(W) Wounds**: How much damage a model can sustain before it is removed from play.  
* **(I) Initiative:** A measure of how quick a model is, which primarily determines attacking order in melee fights.  
* **(A) Attack:** How many times a model may attack in melee combat.  
* **(Ld) Leadership**: A measure of the model’s mental fortitude and ability to deal with psychological effects.  
* **(Sv) Saving Throw**: A measure of the model’s armor and ability to negate suffered wounds. Expressed as die roll value to roll equal to or higher than in order to avoid suffering wounds.

