# **CORE METHODS**

![][image4]

This section describes methods for resolving core activities.  These core methods are referenced throughout the remainder of the rules.

## **MEASUREMENT**

#### **MEASURING DISTANCES**

* All distances are measured in inches.  
* Distances are measured from the closest point to a model’s BASE or HULL directly to the point being measured.  
* Measurements along terrain (e.g. for movement) should be measured along the surface itself, accounting for any slopes or ramps.   
* **No Pre-Measuring:** Players may NOT freely check distances. Distances may only be checked at the specific time when a distance is called to be measured (e.g. when moving models or shooting with weapons and checking range).  
  * **Commit Before Measuring:** Players must decide their action (e.g., fire, charge, move) before measuring distances.  No pre-measuring to decide actions.  
  * **Estimating Distances:** Players must estimate distances to avoid entering charge or shooting range of an enemy. No measuring to ensure distance accuracy before deciding actions.  
  * **Proper Use of Measuring Tools:** Use tape measures or rulers only after committing to an action.  Measure only the action decided upon.  
* If several measurements related to an action are tied for closest (and/or it is difficult to tell exactly which is closest), the player resolving the rule selects which is closest.


#### **WITHIN & WHOLLY WITHIN**

* **MODEL WITHIN**: If a rule says to measure a model “within” a certain distance, any part of the model’s BASE or HULL that is covered by that distance is considered “within.”  
* **MODEL WHOLLY WITHIN:** If a rule says a model must be “wholly within” a certain distance, the entire BASE or HULL of the model must be covered by that distance.  
* **UNIT WITHIN**: A unit is “within” a certain distance if any model of that unit that is within the specified distance.  
* **UNIT WHOLLY WITHIN:** A unit is “wholly within” a certain distance if ALL models in the unit are wholly within the specified distance.


## **MOVING MODELS**

Whenever any type of **MOVEMENT** occurs, the following rules apply, in addition to other rules that might apply based on the type of movement being resolved (see [MOVEMENT PHASE](#movement-phase)).

* **MOVE DISTANCE:** Distances are measured from the forward edge of a model’s base or hull. After completing the move, no part of the base may extend beyond its maximum allowed movement.  
* **TURNING**: Units may adjust the path of their movement in order to traverse around obstacles, and do not need to move in a straight line.  Keep track of the total distance moved for each model that moves.  
* **FACING:** Figurine models have no facing, and may be freely rotated to face any direction when moving. Vehicles do have a facing, and may only be rotated when they are being actively moved.  
* **TERRAIN:** The model’s type determines how it is affected by difficult and dangerous terrain or other obstacles.  
* **MOVING NEAR OTHER MODELS:**   
  * Models may not move through or end their move on top of other models.   
  * Models may move between models of a friendly unit, so long as the unit’s bases can fit between gaps in the unit being moved through.  
  * Models may not move within 1” of an any enemy model (horizontally), unless the specific movement action allows otherwise (e.g. charging into melee combat)  
* **WHICH MODELS MOVED:**   
  * Movement is determined on a model-by-model basis within the unit.    
  * Some models in a unit may move, while others remain stationary.   
  * If any models in the unit move, the unit as a whole counts as having moved, but individual models that remain stationary are still treated as having not moved.  
  * For figurine models, turning the model in place does not count as moving it.  
* **DIFFERENT MOVEMENT SPEEDS:** If a unit contains models of different units types, models may move at different speeds if allowed, so long as the unit remains in coherency at the end of its move.  
* **COHERENCY & MOVEMENT:**   
  * Units must finish moves with all models in the unit within coherency distance.   
  * If it is not possible to move units into coherency, models must move as close as they can to restore coherency. Units out of coherency may suffer morale penalties taking certain tests.  
* **WOBBLY MODELS:** If models are unable to be placed on a piece of terrain due to the need for delicate balancing, players may use a marker or token to track the position of the model until it is moved to a more stable location.

## **LINE OF SIGHT**

Line of sight (LoS) is used to determine what models can “see” other models for purposes of shooting attacks and performing other actions that require LoS.

#### **FIGURINE MODEL LINE OF SIGHT**

* **POINT OF VIEW:** Line of sight is **determined from the eyes** of a figurine  model.  Stoop low/behind the model to get a “model’s eye view” of what the model can “see.” If the location of the model’s eyes are unclear, use a point of view centered on the model’s base and at the top of the model’s **BODY**.  
* **TARGET VISIBILITY:** A target figurine model is in line of sight if any part of the model’s **BODY** (as defined in [MODELS](#models)) is visible from the originating point of view.  Appendages (not part of the body) may be seen through, but if such appendages are all that can be seen, the model is not in line of sight.  
* **BIKES & CAVALRY**: Models mounted on bikes or cavalry are also in line of sight if any part of the bike’s hull/body/wheels or the cavalry mount’s head, body, or upper limbs can be seen.


#### **VEHICLE MODEL LINE OF SIGHT**

* **POINT OF VIEW:** For vehicles, line of sight is measured for each weapon independently, centered on the pivot point of the weapon.   
  * **FIRING ARCS:** Line of sight is further restricted to the firing arc of the weapon based on how it is mounted and its angle of movement.  In cases where weapons are fixed and don’t easily pivot, The firing arc of the weapon is assumed to be a 90-degree wide arc, aligned along the axis of the weapon barrel.  
* **TARGET VISIBILITY**: A target vehicle model is in line of sight if any part of the vehicle’s **HULL** (as defined above) is visible from the originating point of view.  Appendages (not part of the hull) may be seen through, but if that is all that can be seen, the model is not in line of sight.  
* **FIRING PORTS:** Vehicles with firing ports (which allow embarked passengers to shoot out) have a 90-degree wide firing arc, determined for each firing port individually, oriented along the direction of the opening, unless otherwise specified.  
  * Firing ports out of a “top hatch” allow one model to fire with a 360-degree arc.

### Terrain & Blocking Line of Sight

A number of situations, most commonly intervening terrain, can disrupt line of sight between models. As part of setting up terrain for a battle, players must discuss what properties each terrain feature has (see [TERRAIN SETUP](#terrain-setup)).

#### **DENSE COVER (aka AREA TERRAIN)**

* Terrain that provides **dense cover** (aka “area terrain” representing zones of vegetation, dense ruins, etc.) blocks line of sight beyond 6” of total length from the edge of the dense cover, regardless of the actual visibility through the terrain.  
  * Models within 6” of total length from the edge of dense terrain along a line of sight remain visible, but count as **OBSCURED** and will gain **COVER SAVES** (see [SAVING THROWS](#saving-throws)) depending on the terrain type.  
  * Line of sight is blocked by the terrain feature up to the height of the tallest main feature (ignoring banner poles, minor appendages, and other details).  
  * Individual features within a piece of area terrain also count as intervening terrain (see below).  As such, a model may be within 6” of the edge of the area terrain but still entirely out of sight from the point of view of the attacking models.  
* **SEEING OUT:** Models within 6” of the edge of dense cover may “see out” normally and their line of sight is not affected, except by solid intervening terrain pieces. When shooting out of dense cover, their target does not benefit from cover, unless the target itself is also behind cover and/or within the same dense cover terrain.


#### **INTERVENING TERRAIN**

* Non-dense terrain features, such as solid walls, barricades, and hedgerows, may obscure visibility to a model.    
* **OBSCURED:** If any part of a target model’s **body** or **hull** is blocked by intervening terrain features (or the model is in dense cover) but still partially viewable from any point of view from the unit drawing line of sight, then the target counts as being **OBSCURED** and may benefit from being behind cover depending on the type of terrain and receive a **COVER SAVE.**


#### **INTERVENING MODELS**

* **MODELS IN OWN UNIT:** Figurine models in a model’s own unit do not block line of sight.   
* **MODELS IN OTHER UNITS (Friendly or Enemy)**: Figurine models belonging to a different unit, whether friendly or enemy, impacts line of sight and may constitute a **SCREENING** effect (see [SCREENING](#screening)).  
* **VEHICLE MODELS (Friendly or Enemy)**: Vehicle models, whether friendly or enemy, in the same unit or a different one, are treated as intervening terrain and provide a hard cover save to models obscured by them.

## **ROLLING DICE**

#### **TYPES OF INDIVIDUAL DIE ROLLS**

A number of different types of die rolls are used. Specific rules may stipulate that an individual die roll consists of rolling multiple dice as a single roll.

* **D6:** Roll a six-sided dice  
* **D3:** Roll a D6 and divide by 2, rounding up (i.e. 1-2 equals 1; 3-4 equals 2; 5-6 equals 3\)  
* **XD6:** Roll a number of 6-sided dice equal to X (common rolls are a 2D6). When rolling multiple dice as part of a single “roll”, the rule in question will say whether to add the dice totals together, pick the highest/lowest, or something else.  
* **SCATTER DICE**: A scatter die is a special six-sided die with arrows on 4 faces and a HIT marker (also depicting small arrows) on two sides.  Roll scatter on the table as close as possible to the originating location to make it easier to discern the direction indicated.


#### **MODIFYING DIE ROLLS**

* If die rolls are called to be modified, modifiers are applied in the following order: division, multiplication, addition, then subtraction. Round all fractions up.  
* Die rolls cannot be modified to less than a 1\.  
* **UNMODIFIED DIE ROLL**: If a rule references “unmodified dice”, that refers to the natural dice face that is rolled, before accounting for any modifiers.


#### **RE-ROLLS**

* When a **RE-ROLL** is called for, only re-roll the individual dice specified.  
* An individual die roll can only ever be re-rolled once, even if multiple rules allow for re-rolling a certain roll.  
* Re-rolls are applied before any modifiers.


#### **ROLL-OFFS**

* If a roll-off is called for, each player rolls the specified number and type of dice. The player with the highest result is the winner, unless a special rule states otherwise.  If the result is a tie, after accounting for any modifiers, if the special rule does not define a tie breaker, then restart the roll-off.


#### **BATCH ROLLING**

* When multiple die rolls of the same type are called to be rolled at the same time, instead of rolling dice one-by-one, roll as many dice as can logically be rolled together.    
* If there are variations in characteristics that need to be tracked, use different color dice to keep track of specific rolls or sets of rolls.


#### **CHARACTERISTIC TESTS**

* Rules that call for a characteristic test to be made against a model’s Specific characteristic, require the model’s owner to roll a single D6.  The test is passed if the roll is equal to or less than the tested characteristic.   
* **AUTOMATIC PASS/FAIL:** A roll of a 6 always fails and the roll of a 1 always passes, regardless of the actual characteristic value.  
* **LEADERSHIP TEST:** If a **LEADERSHIP TEST** is called for, roll a 2D6 and add the result together.  The test is passed if the total is equal to or less than the model’s leadership. Units containing models with different leadership always use the highest applicable leadership value within the unit.
